# Optional override when the frontend should call the backend directly instead of
# proxying /api and /ws through the frontend server.
# Leave this unset for the default split deployment documented in this repo.
#
# NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL=https://api.example.com
# NEXT_PUBLIC_WS_URL=wss://api.example.com
# API_URL=http://localhost:5005

# Stable player IDs for creator profile links (differ per environment)
# NEXT_PUBLIC_CREATOR_RICO_ID=
# NEXT_PUBLIC_CREATOR_ANDREAS_ID=

# --- OpenPanel (client-side analytics) --------------------------------------
# Both CLIENT_ID and API_URL are required to enable tracking; if either is
# unset the web SDK boots in a disabled (no-op) state. The client id is
# public by design (it ships in the browser bundle) but this repo does not
# ship any specific values — set them in the deploy environment only.
# NEXT_PUBLIC_OPENPANEL_CLIENT_ID=
# NEXT_PUBLIC_OPENPANEL_API_URL=
#
# Dev/prod separation: dev builds NEVER fire OpenPanel events regardless
# of the env vars above — the SDK is lazy-loaded behind a
# `process.env.NODE_ENV !== "production"` gate so it's dead-code-eliminated
# from the dev bundle and never enters the cold compile (2026-04-16).
#
# Previous versions honored `NEXT_PUBLIC_OPENPANEL_ENABLE_IN_DEV=true`
# as an escape hatch, but keeping it around forced Turbopack to include
# the SDK in the dev compile graph and ate ~2-3s per route of cold
# compile. Removed. If you need to smoke-test OpenPanel locally, run
# `NODE_ENV=production next start` against a production build instead.
#
# --- Adblocker-proof proxies (RUNTIME, not build-time) ----------------------
# These are read by server.mjs at startup. They proxy analytics and error
# monitoring requests through the app's own origin so adblockers can't
# distinguish them from regular app traffic.
#
# OPENPANEL_PROXY_URL=https://analytics-api.trebeljahr.com
# GLITCHTIP_PROXY_URL=https://glitchtip.trebeljahr.com

# --- IMPORTANT: NEXT_PUBLIC_* are BUILD-TIME only ---------------------------
# Next.js inlines every `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_*` reference into the
# browser bundle at `next build` time and bakes the result into static
# JS chunks. Runtime env on the running container does NOT reach the
# already-compiled bundle. In Coolify:
#   - Set these as Build-time variables (not just Runtime)
#   - Make sure client/Dockerfile declares each one as an ARG + ENV
#     (see the ARG block at the top of client/Dockerfile)
#   - Trigger a full redeploy after adding or changing a value
# A container restart will NOT pick up changes — the JS has to be rebuilt.
